The paper discusses the use of agent-based modeling and simulation to investigate people management practices in a retail context. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA). Additionally, the paper involves the use of simulation to understand the effects of management practices on retail performance, which could fall under the sub-categories of Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science (cs.CE), Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), and Learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper also focuses on customer satisfaction and service, which could be relevant to the sub-category of Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC).
